<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miners Pay Price for Lackluster Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Gold's status as the ultimate store of value is  
fading, and miners in gold-producing nations are suffering from the 
effects of its plunging price. 
</P>
<P>
	A global gold selloff, hastened by the Bank of England's auction  
of 3.5 percent of its reserves last week, has sent prices down to 
their lowest level in a generation, triggering bankruptcies and 
street protests in South Africa and spreading gloom among miners 
from Uzbekistan to Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	But gold is still coveted by many people around the world.  
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Benn, a 21-year-old London-based fitness instructor, said  
he still has faith in gold's inherent value. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has always been seen as a thing of value. I can understand  
gold. I can't understand all these bonds and when you write a 
check, it's only paper. It's not real money. Gold is real. I can 
understand the solidness of gold -- its simplicity, its purity. It's 
just gold, rather than something symbolic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And gold's falling price has a bright side -- more lavish dowries  
in India and less expensive jewelry in shops in Asia. For many of 
the world's poor, faith in the metal that British economist John 
Maynard Keynes called a ``barbarous relic'' remains strong. 
</P>
<P>
	To wealthier nations, the current era of low inflation and  
peaceful post-Cold War relations have eliminated gold's historic 
role as a solid investment with universal appeal and value. So, 
too, has the increasing popularity of investment alternatives, 
especially stock markets proliferating in rich and poor countries 
alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``The typical reasons for holding gold, at least in developed  
countries, don't exist anymore,'' said John Slater, a research 
economist at Britain's National Westminster Bank Group. ``Gold does 
not provide the function that it used to in terms of a hedge 
against inflation and as a haven against disruption in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Britain announced in May it planned to replace much of its gold  
holdings with higher-yielding assets such as U.S. Treasury bonds. 
Gold prices have plunged 11 percent since then. It closed at 
$257.70 a troy ounce in New York trading Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980 it reached a high of $875 during a period of global  
instability that provided a classic example of gold's value. Soviet 
troops had invaded Afghanistan, U.S. hostages were being held in 
Iran and oil prices were skyrocketing. 
</P>
<P>
	In coming months, prices are likely to drift lower as investors  
anticipate sales of gold by the International Monetary Fund and the 
central bank of Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	To supporters of gold's traditional role, Britain's financial  
authorities ``have lost sight of the reason for having gold 
reserves in the first place -- they are the bastion of a nation's 
currency -- to be used in the last resort when paper money becomes 
unacceptable,'' said Haruko Fukuda of the World Gold Council, a 
London-based group financed by gold mining companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold's decline is most troubling for poorer nations with  
comparatively big gold-mining industries, such as Uzbekistan, Mali 
and Papua New Guinea. Gold is Uzbekistan's second-biggest export 
after cotton, and it accounts for 8 percent of Mali's gross 
domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	At gold's current prices, sub-Saharan African countries,  
excluding South Africa, stand to earn $200 million less than 
expected this year. The IMF, which hopes to help poor countries 
with proceeds from its gold sales, will not be able to fill that 
gap, according to the World Gold Council. 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa, the world's leading gold producer, has one of the  
highest average costs of production, at $246 per ounce. One of the 
country's oldest firms, East Rand Proprietary Mines, announced 
plans Wednesday to liquidate because it could no longer make a 
profit. The liquidation could cost 5,000 mining jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Other mining companies want to lay off an additional 11,700  
workers, a step that prompted a large protest on Thursday in South 
Africa's capital, Pretoria. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's economy is in an ``extremely precarious  
position,'' said David Munro, director of gold banking at The 
Standard Bank of South Africa Ltd. in Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	But cheaper gold is welcome in developing countries. Many Asians  
and Middle Easterners, wary of shaky banks and political 
uncertainty, are firm believers in hoarding gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold jewelry is now more affordable throughout East Asia, where  
the financial crisis that erupted two years ago in Thailand 
reinforced a widespread respect for gold as the safest of 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	In India, a bride's family typically gives gifts of gold jewelry  
to the groom's parents. Anecdotal evidence suggests demand for gold 
in India has risen in the last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in Asia, jewelry is now more affordable in  
pay-by-weight gold shops. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States currently holds half the world's gold  
reserves, but Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has played down the 
possibility that Washington might sell some of its 8,139 metric 
tons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not think the United States should sell its gold, for a  
whole host of reasons,'' Rubin told the House Banking Committee in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	Such words could help soothe tempers in U.S. gold mining states  
such as Nevada, where 8.86 million ounces were produced last year, 
an amount surpassed only by South Africa and Australia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
