<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Crashes at British GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SILVERSTONE, England (AP) -- Two-time world champion Michael  
Schumacher suffered a broken leg but apparently no head or spinal 
injuries as he crashed 30 seconds into the start of Sunday's 
British Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher came out of a turn and, as his brakes seemed to lock  
up, went barreling across the track and into a retaining wall 
traveling at well over 100 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher, 30, was able to climb out of his Ferrari but then  
was placed on a stretcher and given medical attention as he was 
carried to a waiting ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	The immediate medical report said Schumacher had broken his  
right leg but ``was conscious and being air lifted to hospital,'' a 
Formula One spokesman said. The spokesman called his condition 
stable. 
</P>
<P>
	The German didn't look seriously injured as the restart of the  
race was delayed as he and his car were taken away from track. 
</P>
<P>
	The front end of the red Ferrari folded up like an accordion as  
it hit a three-layer deep tire barrier after Schumacher had been 
slowed little going through a gravel shoulder, skating across it 
and hitting the war squarely. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher's crash came as the red flag went up and the start of  
the race had to be abandoned and restarted as two cars stalled on 
the starting line. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury is sure to keep Schumacher out of several races and  
damage his chances of winning this year's series title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
