<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de France Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	METZ, France (AP) -- A look at Sunday's eighth stage of the 86th  
Tour de France: 
</P>
<P>
	STAGE: A 35-mile time trial in the city of Metz.  
</P>
<P>
	WINNER: American Lance Armstrong, riding for the U.S. Postal  
Service team, won the trial in a time of one hour, eight minutes 
and 36 seconds, at an average speed of 30.7 miles per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	HOW OTHERS FARED: In second place for the eighth stage was Alex  
Zulle of Switzerland, and Frenchman Christophe Moreau came in 
third. The world time-trial champion, Abraham Olano of Spain, came 
in fourth, followed by American Tyler Hamilton, also of U.S. 
Postal. Another American, Bobby Julich, who came in third in the 
Tour last year, fell during a steep descent and was forced to 
abandon the race. Julich was riding for the French Cofidis team. 
</P>
<P>
	OVERALL STANDINGS: Armstrong recaptured the leader's yellow  
jersey. Moreau moved into second place, 20 seconds behind the 
leader. Olano edged up to third place, 33 seconds back. Estonian 
Jaan Kirsipuu, riding for the Casino team, slipped from first place 
overall into 11th place. 
</P>
<P>
	TOUR TIDBITS: Armstrong had a full entourage from back home in  
Austin, Texas Sunday: his wife -- who is expecting a baby -- flew in 
for the time trial, as did members of his foundation, which works 
toward the treatment and awareness of testicular cancer. Armstrong 
was diagnosed with the illness in October, 1996 and returned to 
racing early last year after months of treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	QUOTE OF THE DAY: ``It is one of the greatest victories of my  
life,'' Armstrong said. 
</P>
<P>
	NEXT STAGE: Monday is a rest day. Tuesday, a 132.7-mile Alpine  
ride from Le Grand Bornand in the French Alps to Sestrieres in 
Italy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
