<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990711.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 04:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Targeted in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- American troops in the Kosovo  
international peacekeeping force were fired on in three separate 
incidents yesterday but were not hurt. The shootings underscored 
continuing violence and ethnic tensions one month after KFOR, the 
international peacekeeping force, moved into Kosovo under an 
agreement ridding the province of 40,000 Yugoslav military and 
Serbian police forces. Meanwhile, more Russian troops were flown to 
Kosovo to beef up Moscow's peacekeeping contingent that is to 
comprise 3,600 men by the end of the month. 

</P>
<P>
	China Loses World Cup to U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The U.S. team defeated China 5-4  
yesterday on penalty kicks to capture the Women's World Cup soccer 
title. When Brandi Chastain's left-footed kick landed high in the 
net, the Rose Bowl erupted in cheers. U.S. goalie Briana Scurry had 
stopped Liu Ying's shot with the penalty score at 2-2. The game 
remained 0-0 after regulation and two 15-minute overtime. President 
Clinton was one of the 90,185 spectators at the biggest women's 
sporting event in American history. ``It was the most exciting 
sports event I have ever seen,'' Clinton told the victorious U.S. 
athletes. 

</P>
<P>
	Medical Supplies Successfully Dropped at Pole  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- An emergency airdrop of medical  
supplies at the South Pole was completed today. The aid is for a 
worker at Antarctic Support Associates who found a lump in her 
breast, but can't leave the continent until October, when aircraft 
can safely land on the continent. Base staff at the Amundsen-Scott 
South Pole Station had just seven minutes in the winter blackness 
and the freezing temperatures to collect six pallets of supplies 
before the extreme cold would damage or destroy the drugs and 
equipment they carried. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Mars Berlin Love Parade  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- An estimated 1.4 million yesterday bounced to the  
techno throb of the Love Parade, the annual all-weekend rave billed 
as the world's largest street party. But the parade was not all 
festive. One person was stabbed to death during a fight, police 
said. Police said they had no suspects, and further details were 
not immediately available. Since the Love Parade started in 1988, 
when a small group danced behind a VW van through then-West Berlin, 
the event has drawn increasingly large crowds -- to the dismay of 
environmentalists. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Testing New Air Traffic System  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) -- The future of air traffic control got a  
flight test yesterday as more than a dozen planes with 
satellite-positioning systems flew over Ohio and Kentucky while 
monitors tracked the exact location of each aircraft. The ``ADS-B'' 
system, more accurate than radar and with a longer range than 
existing collision-avoidance systems, simultaneously gives air 
traffic controllers and pilots an instant look at where the 
airplanes were and whether any were on conflicting courses. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Preventive Care Benefit  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton yesterday said older  
Americans who rely on Medicare must receive affordable preventive 
care. In his weekly radio address, Clinton said: ``No senior should 
have to hesitate to get the preventive care they need.'' He wants 
to eliminate Medicare co-payments and deductibles for preventive 
medical care such as hepatitis B vaccinations, colo-rectal and 
prostate cancer screening and diabetes management. 

</P>
<P>
	Aryan Nations Stage Parade  
</P>
<P>
	COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) -- Under the protection of a federal  
court order, members of the Aryan Nations yesterday paraded through 
downtown streets. But they were outshouted by protesters who forced 
the marchers to detour. Four protesters were arrested. After the 
20-minute parade, some of the two dozen Aryans saluted supporters 
in the crowd with the Nazi straight-arm gesture. City officials had 
urged people to ignore the march, but thousands of opponents 
gathered along the parade route, chanting ``No Nazis! No KKK! No 
fascists! USA!'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Crush White Sox 10-22  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jon Lieber supplied strong pitching and Jose  
Hernandez and Glenallen Hill homered today as the Chicago Cubs 
finally beat the crosstown White Sox 10-2. The White Sox won the 
first four meetings this season. Lieber (8-3) allowed seven hits in 
eight innings. 

</P>
<P>
	Dougherty Ahead at Senior Open  
</P>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Ed Dougherty's 3-over 75 today left  
him with a one-shot lead after three rounds of the U.S. Senior Open 
golf tournament. Dougherty's 54-hole score was 4-under 212. A 
stroke back were Bruce Summerhays, defending champion Hale Irwin 
and Dave Eichelberger 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
