<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUDON, N.H. (AP) -- Hall of Fame driver Buddy Baker was among  
the least surprised of those who watched rookie Tony Stewart 
dominate the Jiffy Lube 300 -- his first Winston Cup event at New 
Hampshire International Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for Stewart, he ran out of gas with two laps  
remaining -- giving Jeff Burton his third straight victory in the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can drive anywhere or any surface,'' Baker, now a  
commentator who worked the race for TNN, said of Stewart before the 
race Sunday. ``It doesn't matter if it's dirt, pavement, a road 
course, whatever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said he has been impressed with the 28-year-old rookie  
since first seeing him race in the USAC midgets, sprints and Silver 
Crown cars nearly a decade ago. Baker wasn't surprised that Stewart 
became the 1997 Indy Racing League champion, and figures there are 
many NASCAR victories ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Baker, Stewart has a special ingredient --  
indomitable courage -- that will make him a big star in the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tony Stewart is the bravest driver I've ever seen,'' Baker  
said. ``I remember seeing him in a Silver Crown car, passing six 
cars on the apron. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `He's dead,' but he made it through.''  
</P>
<P>
	Baker likens Stewart to three-time Winston Cup champion Jeff  
Gordon, saying both were born with immense ability to drive, but 
developed beyond that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jeff Gordon won 500 races before he even got into a Busch  
car,'' Baker said. ``I looked at him and I said, `God, that's 
somebody's child out there.' 
</P>
<P>
	``But he's no child. That's a man in the race car.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARTIN'S DAY:* With Tony Stewart running out of gas, Jeff  
Burton winning his third straight Jiffy Lube 300 and Jeff Gordon 
bumping and banging with Dale Jarrett and Rusty Wallace, hardly 
anyone paid any attention to Mark Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	But his was the most inspirational story of the race, a wounded  
warrior who had to be lifted into his car. He not only drove all 
300 laps, he finished sixth despite a broken rib, leg and wrist -- 
injuries sustained nine days earlier in a practice crash at Daytona 
International Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	So, how did Martin feel about all this?  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I said Friday we'd be real disappointed if we didn't get  
a top five,'' he said. ``So we're a little disappointed'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS:* Iron man Terry Labonte extended the Winston Cup  
record for consecutive starts to 620 when the green flag fell on 
the Jiffy Lube 300. Labonte, who has 625 starts overall, has run 
every race in the series since 1979. He finished 11th. ... 
Seven-time series champion Dale Earnhardt restored order in his 
family by finishing seventh, 36 positions ahead of son Dale Jr. -- 
making just his second Winston Cup start. The elder Earnhardt has 
expressed disappointment over qualifying 14th Friday after his son 
earned the 13th spot on the grid. But it wasn't much of a contest 
because the younger Earnhardt went out after 44 laps with an 
ignition problem. ... Joe Falk, unable to attract sponsorship for 
his team, carried the Kodiak colors Sunday because Larry Hedrick's 
team failed to qualify for the race. Dick Trickle drove Falk's 
Chevrolet to a 29th-place finish. Roush Racing, which failed to 
land a car as high as 25th on the starting grid, did much better in 
the race. Jeff Burton won, Mark Martin finished sixth, Johnny 
Benson 17th, Kevin Lepage 22nd and Chad Little 24th. ... Baseball 
Hall of Famer Ted Williams was the grand marshal for the race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
