<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Likely To Veto GOP Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is passing the word  
that Republican lawmakers can expect a presidential veto if they 
send the White House a big tax-cut bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Newly installed Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said  
President Clinton ``absolutely'' would reject a bill promising as 
much as $800 billion in tax cuts, the amount GOP leaders are 
promoting. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Summers also  
voiced strong support for Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board 
chairman whose third four-year term expires next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, Chairman Greenspan has done a terrific job, and I  
have very much enjoyed working with him and look forward to working 
with him going forward,'' said Summers, formerly the deputy 
treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	But, asked whether Clinton might reappoint Greenspan now to keep  
the job from becoming a political factor in the 2000 presidential 
campaign, Summers said: ``We've got enormous confidence in Chairman 
Greenspan. Let me leave it at that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On taxes, both Summers and the White House chief of staff, John  
Podesta, said Clinton would support a cut in the $250 billion 
range. But they said the GOP alternative would threaten defense and 
domestic programs, what Summers called ``core government, 
everything from the national parks to the FBI to medical 
research.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and Republicans agree that reinforcing Social Security  
and Medicare should be the top priority for most of a projected 
$2.9 trillion budget surplus over the next 10 years. Those benefit 
programs are threatened by the aging of the massive post-World War 
II baby boom generation. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties disagree, however, on how to safeguard the programs  
and what to do with around $1 trillion that would be left over. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, Republicans want to return much of it in lower taxes,  
which Democrats say would mean tax breaks for the rich. Democrats 
want to use it for much smaller tax cuts and for more generous 
upgrades of Medicare and additional spending on such programs as 
education. The GOP criticizes that as a big-government 
tax-and-spend policy. 
</P>
<P>
	On ABC's ``This Week,'' Podesta said the latest House proposal,  
a 10 percent across-the-board tax cut proposed by Rep. Bill Archer, 
R-Texas, the Ways and Means Committee chairman, would cost the 
government $179 billion more in interest payments than if the 
surplus were used to pay down debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Congressional Budget Office's projected surplus totals  
$996 billion, and Archer's tax cut would be $864 billion, that 
would put government in deficit by $47 billion, Podesta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said such proposals create a cost ``that is exploding,  
that is on a takeoff path out beyond 10 years, that would threaten 
all we've worked hard to do in terms of creating budget surpluses 
and would do a great deal of damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he thought  
Summers' comments still ``left room for discussion in a number of 
areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's good that the secretary of the treasury is here  
talking about what we do with this surplus we now have, and I think 
that a good portion of it should be returned to the people that are 
now being overtaxed,'' Lott said on NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added: ``I keep getting mixed signals from the president.  
I don't know whether he wants to get some things done through 
cooperation, or whether he's going to go the partisan route, the 
political route.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and other congressional leaders of both parties were  
meeting with Clinton late today. If the president opts for 
bipartisanship, Lott said, ``We can do it together. ... I hope that 
he'll approach it that way. Not where can we disagree, but where 
can we agree.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Summers said Clinton continues to stress spending  
for Social Security, Medicare and ``the needs of the vast majority 
of American families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are other needs and other issues, and certainly we're  
prepared to talk about things,'' he said, ``but the main issue has 
to be putting our priorities very clear.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
