<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Early in the week the volunteers at  
the merchandise tent worked hard to keep shelves stocked with 
jackets, hats, shirts and other U.S. Senior Open souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who didn't buy a keepsake before Sunday was in trouble.  
Many of the shelves in the sprawling tent were empty. Tables near 
the checkout stands, packed days earlier with golf balls, keychains 
and other trinkets, were bare. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans came through the tent anyway, some of them curious and  
others hunting for a last-chance bargain. The cash registers beeped 
and clicked as a steady stream of hundreds filtered across the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll buy a cap or a shirt, if I can find one,'' said Jess  
Murillo, 49, an accountant from Johnston, Iowa. ``Right now, the 
options are pretty limited. It's my first time through here all 
week. I should have bought something before.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BACK TO IOWA:* Champion Dave Eichelberger has been here before.  
He played the U.S. Amateur at Wakonda Club in Des Moines in 1963, 
which until this week was the last time the USGA staged a 
tournament in Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Eichelberger said he felt more confident going into that event  
than he did at the Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a sophomore in college and was playing pretty good at  
Oklahoma State,'' he said. ``There were just a lot of guys that 
were really good players, and I was beating them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He reached the third round of the Amateur before being  
eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BARNES WITHDRAWS:* Brian Barnes had a painful week.  
</P>
<P>
	The Scotsman withdrew Sunday on the ninth hole, complaining of  
severe pain in his hands and feet stemming from rheumatoid 
arthritis. His left hand was so painful early in the round, he 
could barely grip his club. 
</P>
<P>
	``My driver, I almost missed the bloody thing on five, almost  
missed it on six, almost missed it on seven,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes also had trouble walking without pain on the back nine  
all week. When his knuckles flared up, he knew it was time to load 
up his motor home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It started to hurt badly on the range this morning, and I knew  
it was not going to be too good,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes was 4-over starting the final round and 1-over through  
eight holes. He canceled an exhibition Monday in Toronto but said 
he plans to return to Scotland for the British Senior Open in two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ATTENDANCE OVERLOAD:* The fans in Des Moines loved the Senior  
Open. And the players loved the fans, all 252,800 of them. 
</P>
<P>
	The attendance Sunday was 51,200, the seventh day of increases  
that started with 25,000 spectators for Monday's practice round. 
The crowd climbed to 27,000 on Tuesday, then 29,000 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	For Thursday's opening round, it was 35,000. On Friday, the  
figure climbed to 38,400 and Saturday's crowd was 47,200. 
</P>
<P>
	USGA officials have said there are no records for attendance  
because they don't want to compare cities or golf courses. But all 
have agreed the fans in Iowa have turned out like no other Senior 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up Ed Dougherty said starting with his practice rounds,  
he didn't want to disappoint so many people. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care whether you're an amateur playing in the U.S.  
Open or a grizzly old tour veteran,'' he said. ``If you have 25,000 
people out there, you want to perform. Your motor goes on, and I 
think this crowd brought out our best.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROCKY THE ROCKET:* Rocky Thompson wasn't planning to stick  
around. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting the final round at 15-over 231, Thompson was the first  
player to tee off Sunday morning. He played alone and finished his 
round in 2 hours, 15 minutes. An hour later, the first paired 
players came in. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson shot a final-round 80 for a 72-hole total of 311.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PLEASE BE POLITE:* You'd think most people who buy a ticket to  
a golf tournament would be familiar with golf etiquette. To be on 
the safe side, the daily pairing sheet offered tips for spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	There were obvious suggestions like observing silence through  
each shot, staying behind the gallery ropes and obeying course 
marshals. It also was advised to wear low-heeled shoes ``for your 
sake and the sake of the golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And above all, don't forget: ``It is most inappropriate to  
applaud or cheer the misplays or misfortunes of a player.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
