<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary and History's Carpetbag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was just a valise, a cheap and flexible  
travelers bag stitched together from pieces of patterned carpet -- 
in short, a carpetbag. 
</P>
<P>
	But used as a symbol, the carpetbag, that homely and practical  
19th century satchel, has emerged from the past to become one of 
the more pungent jibes in American politics. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is said to be carrying one as  
she moves from the White House into the race for the Senate from 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	She is, her critics say, a certified nonresident, an outsider,  
an unworthy opportunist seeking political power at the expense of 
local politicians -- a ``carpetbagger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need someone from Arkansas or Illinois, coming in and  
trying to learn about our state in the hopes of being sent back to 
Washington,'' New York's Republican governor, George Pataki, said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The cry of ``carpetbagger' has been heard before in New York  
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Robert F. Kennedy, a Democrat from Massachusetts, and James  
Buckley, a Republican from Connecticut, ran as outsiders for the 
Senate from New York. Both were called carpetbaggers. Both won. In 
Kennedy's case, New Yorkers ignored such gaffes as being addressed 
as, ``Fellow New Yorkites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Times columnist and word expert William Safire says  
``carpetbagger'' was used originally to describe itinerant bankers 
with meager means who operated in the sparsely settled countryside 
in the years before the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	The word likely gained currency on Deep South railway platforms  
in the late 1860s when sharp-eyed and resentful ex-Confederates 
observed lean and hungry-looking Northerners stepping off 
southbound trains with all their worldly goods stuffed into a 
single bag, often a carpetbag. 
</P>
<P>
	``The carpetbag was the symbol of the man who traveled light,  
and hence of the man on the make,'' Safire wrote in ``Safire's 
Political Dictionary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the victorious North tried to reconstruct the defeated South  
after the Civil War, the unwelcome carpetbagger was seen by many 
Southerners as an instrument of unwanted change, an exploiter who 
left social unrest and financial corruption in his wake. 
</P>
<P>
	But to others, many of these Northern carpetbaggers were heroes  
who put the war-devastated Southern states back on their feet and 
tried genuinely to help newly enfranchised black citizens exercise 
their political right. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19th century cartoonist Thomas Nast, credited for creating  
both the Republican elephant and the Democratic donkey, was quick 
to pick up the carpetbag. 
</P>
<P>
	An 1872 Nast cartoon showed long-legged Carl Schurz, a prominent  
German-American newspaper editor and Civil War general, carrying 
carpetbags from Wisconsin to Missouri to win a Senate seat. One 
satchel carries the label, ``Carpetbagger South.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the 1870s, Reconstruction was over; white  
Southerners regained political power. According to some present-day 
historians, they also wrote much of the history of what had 
happened, giving carpetbaggers the evil eye in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	As far as the Senate is concerned, an out-of-state birthplace  
has never been a disqualification. 
</P>
<P>
	As the United States moved west, many senators in newly  
organized states were born elsewhere. ``It was part of the natural 
flow of migration,'' said Richard Baker, the Senate's historian. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said the record is held by Irish-born Sen. James Shields,  
who served from three states -- Illinois, Minnesota and Missouri -- 
in the 19th century. 
</P>
<P>
	In this century, moving from one state to another to seek a  
political opening is far from unknown. Winthrop Rockefeller moved 
far from his gilded New York roots to serve as governor of Arkansas 
in the 1960s. His nephew, Jay Rockefeller, is in his third term as 
a Democratic senator from West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Safire concluded in his dictionary that voters may be less  
concerned than before with a politician's birthplace. 
``Carpetbagger just doesn't seem as dirty a word as it once was,'' 
he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Safire was not referring specifically to Mrs. Clinton in the  
book, published years before her candidacy became a possibility. He 
has been a frequent critic of the first lady in his columns, at one 
point calling her ``a congenital liar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If New York voters do choose to ignore the carpetbagger cries  
they will, at the least, shatter two centuries of expectations 
about the limits surrounding America's first ladies and their 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, meanwhile, tells audiences she does not resent the  
carpetbagger allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Her job now, she says, is to convince folks that ``what I'm for  
is maybe as important -- if not more important -- than where I'm 
from.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990711.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell's Slam Makes Fan a Millionaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- With one swing of the bat, Jay Bell made Gylene  
Hoyle a millionaire. She never saw the ball hit the seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had my eyes closed at that point,'' she said. ``I didn't  
actually know he'd hit the home run until everyone around me 
started yelling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoyle, a 31-year-old child care provider from nearby Chandler,  
won the $1 million prize in the Diamondbacks' grand slam contest. 
At every Sunday home game since the Diamondbacks began play last 
year, there has been a contest where a fan wins tickets, then picks 
a player to hit a grand slam and the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	She won the game tickets and the right to be the grand slam  
contest entrant through KNIX, a Phoenix country music station. She 
figured the odds that she'd win the $1 million were astronomical. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just happy to get into the game because we'd never been  
here before,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoyle chose Bell ``because the rest of my family are big  
Diamondbacks fans and they said he was the best hitter with the 
most home runs.'' Her husband Clayton, a drill rig operator, 
suggested the sixth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Bingo.  
</P>
<P>
	After Tony Womack drew a two-out walk, the bases were loaded as  
Bell walked to the plate. He already knew she had chosen him and 
the sixth inning. He was 0-for-12 in the three-game series against 
the A's. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no question I wanted to hit a home run there,'' Bell  
said. ``I saw her on our dugout before the game and knew the whole 
situation. Most of the fans did, too. It was a lot of fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the A's Jimmy Haynes on the mound, Bell worked the count to  
3-1, then fouled a couple pitches into the seats. The last foul 
barely escaped the reach of catcher Ramon Hernandez. A few rows up 
behind the Arizona dugout, sitting with her husband and her two 
children, Colleen 8, and Clayton II, 7, Hoyle was going crazy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were counting players. I was saying, `Jay Bell isn't going  
to make it in the sixth' and my husband said, `You know, anything 
could happen,' '' she said. ``Then when he got up there and the 
bases were loaded, I just cringed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the foul balls went into the stands, ``my stomach was in  
knots,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he hit it,'' she said, ``I was ecstatic.''  
</P>
<P>
	Haynes delivered a fastball up and over the plate, and Bell hit  
into the left-field seats for his 24th homer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where's my share?'' Haynes said. ``Maybe I had greater powers  
working against me today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's slam was the fifth of his career and his first in two  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was 1-for-14 in the series,'' he said, ``and that hit was  
very special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Hoyle seemed almost in shock. She hugged Bell outside  
the Diamondbacks' clubhouse and talked about what she'd do with the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea,'' she said, ``other than take a well-deserved  
vacation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her daughter already had an idea. ``I want to go to  
Disneyland,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoyle wasn't sure if she'd quit taking care of other people's  
children, despite her newfound wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really like the kids I have,'' she said, ``but I won't take  
any more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
