<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Iran Fires Two Security Chiefs  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iran's government today fired  
two security chiefs responsible for a violent assault on a student 
hostel, Tehran television reported. The National Security Council 
issued a statement saying that Brig. Gen. Sadat Ahmadi and his 
deputy have been dismissed and would be handed over to judiciary 
officials, the television said in a broadcast monitored in Dubai. 
Police and hard-line activists stormed a Tehran University 
dormitory in the early hours of Friday after a small demonstration 
by reformist students. Some 20 people were admitted to hospital. 

</P>
<P>
	China Calls Taiwan President a Liar  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China criticized Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui as  
a separatist and a liar today in one of its most direct and 
harshest attacks on the leader of the rival government in three 
years. Lee drew the heated response by telling German radio station 
Deutche Welle that Taiwan and China should see each other as two 
separate countries. China insists that the mainland and island, 
which separated amid civil war 50 years ago, are one country. The 
statement by the spokesman for the Communist Party's Taiwan affairs 
offices said Lee's remarks violate his pledge not to lead Taiwan 
toward independence. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Fired Upon in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Gunmen fired on American troops of  
the Kosovo international peacekeeping force in three separate 
incidents but no U.S. service members were hurt, a military 
spokesman said today. The shootings underscored continuing violence 
and ethnic tensions one month after KFOR, the international 
peacekeeing force, moved into Kosovo. In southwestern Orahovac, 
ethnic Albanians marched through the town's center today to protest 
plans to deploy Russian soldiers in the sector of Bosnia controlled 
by German peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	Srebrenica Survivors Mark Massacre  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Thousands of women and  
children, who survived Bosnia's biggest massacre, took to the 
streets today to commemorate the fall of the Muslim enclave of 
Srebrenica four years ago. Starting July 11, 1995, Bosnian Serb 
forces overran the eastern Bosnian enclave, which was a 
U.N.-protected zone. Up to 8,000 men and boys older than 14 went 
missing. Bosnian Muslims blame the United Nations for the massacre 
because the U.N. Security Council passed a resolution declaring 
Srebrenica a ``safe area'' under its protection, but didn't do 
anything when Serb forces overran it. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Make Peace Promise  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israel's Prime Minister  
Ehud Barak held his first summit today with Palestinian leader 
Yasser Arafat and emerged pledging to ``move forward in peace'' 
together. ``Both sides have suffered enough,'' the new Israeli 
prime minister said, as Arafat looked on, nodding. ``It is time to 
put an end to the cycle of violence and confrontation,'' Arafat 
said. The session at a border crossing between Israel and the Gaza 
Strip lasted little over an hour. 

</P>
<P>
	Jets Deliver Antarctic Supplies  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- A military flight crew guided  
by a C-shaped line of barrels blazing in the freezing darkness 
swooped down to drop emergency medical supplies to a South Pole 
research station today. The drop zone was 150 feet from the 
buildings at the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station, where a worker 
with a lump in one breast urgently needs treatment, but the extreme 
conditions at the coldest spot on Earth an she cannot be evacuated 
until late October. 

</P>
<P>
	NAACP Celebrates 90th Birthday  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP yesterday recommitted itself to  
confronting issues affecting black America. The affirmation came as 
the nation's largest and oldest civil rights organization 
celebrated its 90th birthday on the opening day of a six-day 
convention in New York. ``This convention will be celebratory, but 
we will also be looking back towards the principles we were founded 
on,'' said Julian Bond, the NAACP's national board chairman. ``It's 
nice to reminisce, but we can't afford not to keep looking 
forward.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Coulthard Takes British Grand Prix  
</P>
<P>
	SILVERSTONE, England (AP) -- David Coulthard rejoined the Formula  
One title chase today by winning the British Grand Prix, a race in 
which Michael Schumacher broke his leg in a crash in the first 30 
seconds. Eddie Irvine of Northern Ireland was second in a Ferrari, 
with Ralf Schumacher third in a Williams. Michael Schumacher rammed 
a retaining wall at more than 100 mph, breaking his right leg but 
avoiding back or spinal injuries. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
