<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Campaign Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Amid rumblings he might drop from the  
presidential race, House Budget Committee chairman John Kasich said 
Sunday he wasn't certain whether he would proceed with his 
long-shot bid for the Republican nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we get to the point where we've made a decision and are  
going to talk about it, we'll let you know,'' the Ohio Republican 
said when asked about rumors he might drop from the race and 
endorse another candidate this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether a decision had been made, Kasich said he would  
talk about it when he was ready. 
</P>
<P>
	His spokesman, Todd Harris, said that unlike some other  
Republican hopefuls who are certain they will run, Kasich only has 
an exploratory committee and has just been exploring his chances. 
He said he didn't know how much more exploring Kasich had to do 
before announcing a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	If Kasich were to give up his shot at the nomination, he would  
be the first dropout among 12 Republicans. Most analysts believe 
that field will be reduced significantly following next month's 
straw poll in Iowa, if not before. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush has dominated the Republican slate of  
candidates, in the polls and in campaign fund raising. Kasich has 
fared poorly in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican analyst Tom Rath of Concord said that at the  
Republican National Committee meeting in Philadelphia last week, he 
heard Kasich and other cash-strapped candidates may be close to 
dropping out. But he said he did know of any final decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money and political reality are going to force a lot of these  
people to take a look at where they are,'' Rath said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former Vice President  
Dan Quayle have cut staff and travel plans because of low 
fund-raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich met with a dozen residents at a historic carriage house  
in Concord on Sunday in his 10th trip to the state with the 
earliest primary. He portrayed himself as a down-to-earth guy, 
telling stories of speaking with voters who didn't realize they 
were talking to a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	He also talked about the difficulties government poses to small  
businesses, and said Americans should have more faith and humility. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have humility, you don't have road rage,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
