<HEADLINE> Storms Wash Away Cars in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN BERNARDINO NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. (AP) -- Flash floods swept  
cars and cabins into a creek Sunday afternoon as storms rolled 
through Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1 1/2 inches of rain flooded the Forest Falls area of the San  
Bernardino National Forest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have reports of numerous cars off the roads and several  
cabins washed off into the creek,'' said David McLees, battalion 
chief for the San Bernardino County Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
	There were reports of injuries, he said, including head injuries  
and people trapped in the mud. He did not know how many people were 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a narrow canyon area and when the rain comes down real  
hard, it focuses right there where residents are,'' McLees said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there were many homes, rented cabins and a conference  
center in the forest, about 85 miles east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles County, firefighters rescued about 100 hikers and  
picnickers stranded in Azusa Canyon, said Mark Whaling, a spokesman 
for the county Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain in the upper portion of the canyon north of Los Angeles  
caused the level of a nearby river to rise two feet, making it hard 
to cross. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were people covered with mud,'' he said. ``Some people  
got swept down a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rain was part of a monsoon pattern drawing moisture inland  
from the southwest, forecasters said. A 40 percent chance of 
showers was expected throughout Southern California Monday 
afternoon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
