<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Budweiser Takes Czech Firm to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- The maker of top-selling Budweiser beer in Hong  
Kong has taken a Czech rival to court in the latest skirmish in 
their long-standing trademark battle, a newspaper reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch said in court papers that Budejovicky Budvar beer  
had infringed on the St. Louis-based brewer's trademark since 
Budejovicky is the Czech word for Budweiser, the Sunday Morning 
Post reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. brewer is seeking a court order to have the Czech  
company's products taken off the shelves in Hong Kong, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch has launched similar lawsuits in Europe and the  
United States. It says the Czech brewery is mimicking its name to 
confuse beer drinkers and cash in on the U.S. company's success. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Czechs say they had claims to the name long before the  
Americans began brewing beer. ``Budweiser,'' named after a Czech 
village called Ceske Budejovice, was made as far back as the Middle 
Ages, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The term Budweiser simply describes beer from that region, the  
same way Burgundy and Champagne describe wine from those 
wine-making regions of France, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The German immigrants who founded Anheuser-Busch in 1876 used  
the Budweiser name for their beer because it was well-known in 
their homeland. In Czechoslovakia, the state-owned Budvar brewery 
was founded in 1895. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czech brewery exports to 37 countries, mainly in Europe.  
Anheuser-Busch has sales in more than 70 countries around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, federal regulators in the United States began  
investigating whether the Czech brewer's use of the ``Budweiser 
Budvar'' label violates U.S. trademark law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
