<HEADLINE> Yankees Promote Lefty Ed Yarnall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Yankees, still trying to settle  
their pitching staff, promoted left-hander Ed Yarnall from Triple-A 
Columbus on Sunday and sent reliever Todd Erdos back to the minor 
league club. 
</P>
<P>
	Yarnall, 23, was leading the International League in wins and  
strikeouts, and was picked for the IL's All-Star team. He was 10-3 
with a 3.29 ERA in 17 starts, striking out 113 in 109 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Yarnall was 4-0 with a 1.99 ERA in his last six starts, and had  
not lost in a span of 10 starts since May 14. Never before in the 
majors, he was recalled prior to the Yankees playing the New York 
Mets in the wrapup of the three-game Subway Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees got Yarnall from Florida last February in a trade  
that sent third baseman Mike Lowell to Florida. In May 1998, 
Yarnall was 7-0 with an 0.39 ERA at Double-A Binghamton when the 
New York Mets traded him to the Marlins as part of a package for 
Mike Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret that we've been looking for a second  
left-hander in our bullpen to go with Mike Stanton,'' Yankees 
general manager Brian Cashman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had been looking at him for our rotation in 2000,'' he  
said. ``But he's here now and we'll see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The AL East-leading Yankees have been exploring trade  
possibilities involving struggling left-handed starter Andy 
Pettitte. They have been trying to add a second lefty in the 
bullpen ever since sending Graeme Lloyd to Toronto in part of this 
year's deal for Roger Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Erdos, a 25-year-old righty, was 0-0 in four games for the  
Yankees. He allowed three earned runs in seven innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
