<HEADLINE> Small Quakes Rumble Sierra Nevada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE ISABELLA, Calif. (AP) -- A moderate earthquake and two  
smaller ones shook the southern Sierra Nevada on Sunday, but no 
injuries or damage were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest of the quakes had a 4.3-magnitude and struck the  
Kern County region at 11:20 a.m., according to seismologist Karen 
Kahler of the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena. The 
epicenter was about 38 miles northeast of Bakersfield. 
</P>
<P>
	A magnitude-3.4 quake shook the same area at 11:22 a.m.,  
followed by a magnitude-3.1 temblor about seven minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first it was just felt like the windows were shaking, then  
sit stopped and all of the sudden they started shaking again,'' 
said John Carter, manager of the Lake Isabella Motel. 
</P>
<P>
	Kern County sheriff's dispatcher Chris Johnson said there were  
no reports of damages or injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Lake Isabella is about 180 miles north of downtown Los Angeles.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
