<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Denounced for Attack on Smith </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several Republican presidential candidates  
criticized their own party Sunday for attacking conservative Sen. 
Bob Smith, who is expected to quit the GOP and run for president 
under a third party. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan, both seeking the GOP nomination  
for president in 2000, defended Smith's decision to bolt the party 
and they blamed the GOP for the defection, saying the party has 
abandoned conservative ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	Both said they would remain in the GOP.  
</P>
<P>
	A fourth GOP presidential contender, Steve Forbes, said the GOP  
``should stop running people out of the party'' and ``go back to 
our core principles.'' Forbes said he has no intention of leaving 
the party. 
</P>
<P>
	The bickering broke out Friday after the chairman of the  
Republican National Committee, Jim Nicholson, and other GOP leaders 
were sharply critical of Smith's planned defection, which he 
expects to announce this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision is a ``serious mistake for you personally, with  
only a marginal political impact -- and a counterproductive one at 
that,'' Nicholson told Smith in a letter. ``This would not be a 
case of the party leaving you, Bob, but rather of you leaving our 
party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter responding to Nicholson's criticisms, Bauer defended  
Smith, a New Hampshire Republican whom he called ``a man of deep 
conviction and unwavering principle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like millions of other Republicans, (Smith) is concerned by  
the retreat of our party's leadership on matters of fundamental 
principle,'' Bauer wrote to Nicholson. 
</P>
<P>
	RNC spokesman Mike Collins said Sunday that Nicholson's letter  
was a ``frank and honest expression of his disappointment that a 
principled, lifelong Republican would find it necessary to abandon 
the Reagan coalition and go his own way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only real political impact of Smith's defection would be to  
help the Democrats, Collins said in an interview. ``It could 
possibly supply some marginal support for Al Gore,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Bauer's outspokenness in defending Smith, he does not  
plan to follow suit and abandon the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have absolutely no intention of leaving the Republican  
Party,'' Bauer said Sunday through spokesman Tim Goeglein. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, campaigning in Iowa, has urged Smith's supporters to  
remain in the Republican party and join Bauer's campaign, Goeglein 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan said Nicholson's letter was ``rude and insulting and  
ultimately very stupid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the handling of this has been appalling,'' Buchanan  
said Sunday on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan said he would not rule anything out when asked whether  
he would consider ditching the GOP and running as a third party 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, Forbes, speaking on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' said that  
``instead of haranguing Bob Smith,'' the GOP should convene a 
series of debates among GOP presidential candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need these debates so Republican voters can decide what our  
principles are,'' said Forbes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
