<DOCNO> APW19990711.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Assure Customers Over Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- No novice to online banking, Andrea Kovar zooms  
money around daily from her personal computer. But because she 
depends heavily on electronic funds transfers, she worries about 
the millennium bug. 
</P>
<P>
	Kovar is one of 100 million consumers, including most Social  
Security recipients, who have their paycheck or government benefits 
deposited electronically. Some 4 million people pay bills by 
computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Because online bankers could be especially inconvenienced when  
the calendar rolls over on Jan. 1, banks and the federal government 
are testing and retesting their systems to make sure the year 2000 
arrives without hassles. 
</P>
<P>
	Kovar, a Coon Rapids, Minn., radio station manager, has seen  
their reassuring press releases. Still, she worries. What if the 
much-discussed computer glitch delays the automatic deposit of her 
paycheck, or the payment of some crucial bill? What if a late 
mortgage or utility payment damages her credit rating, which she 
has taken pains to repair over the past few years? 
</P>
<P>
	``You're a few days late on something, and they hit you with all  
kinds of service charges,'' Kovar said. ``To clear those things up 
takes 10 to 15 minutes, easy, out of a business day. None of us has 
the time to try to clean up messes that somebody else has 
created.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve Board says it is ready to answer questions  
like hers. In addition to testing its electronic settlement 
systems, the Fed has ordered an extra $50 billion of new currency 
to put into circulation to cover a spate of potential cash 
withdrawals around the new year. It has proposed an emergency loan 
fund for banks, thrifts and credit unions to cover extra 
withdrawals. And it has ordered at least one big ATM operator, 
TransAlliance LP, to get in shape for year 2000 or face possible 
contract cancellations by its 750 bank customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers will have limited recourse if problems do occur.  
Congress earlier this month enacted legislation, which President 
Clinton is expected to sign, that would make lawsuits difficult or 
impossible. A number of states have similar laws on their books. 
</P>
<P>
	But the same bill also prohibits lenders from taking adverse  
action against homeowners whose mortgage payments are delayed by 
Y2K problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the preparation that the Fed has taken, it is proudest of  
its rigorous testing procedures. Along with four regional 
organizations that settle electronic transactions, the Fed last 
month successfully finished testing its computer fix by rolling 
dates forward to Jan. 1 and running simulated financial 
transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	The result? ``The financial industry, we feel, is very ready for  
year 2000,'' a Fed spokeswoman said. ``We're not going to say 
there's not going to be glitches. There are glitches every day. But 
if it doesn't work on Jan. 1, is it a Y2K problem? Maybe. But maybe 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called ``Y2K problem'' is caused by the possibility that  
computers originally programmed to recognize only the last two 
digits of a year could interpret 2000 as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	One solution was to add the first two digits back into the data  
entries, but that proved too complicated and expensive for most 
organizations. Instead, the Automated Clearing House, the national 
electronic banking network, did a temporary fix that will solve the 
problem through 2073. The systems that process paper checks and 
automated teller machine transactions have taken similar measures. 
</P>
<P>
	In large part because regulators have insisted on it, the  
banking industry is ahead of most in addressing the Year 2000 
problem. It is also ahead because it has spent a lot of money on 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	But having been early adopters of computer technology, banks  
have relatively old systems. ``There's all kinds of time bombs in 
there,'' said Gary Arlen, a Bethesda, Md., computer industry 
analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	And like most other industries, banks rely on telecommunications  
systems and electric utilities that may not be as prepared. Some 
technology experts worry that the bug could still cause computers 
to miscalculate loan payments or due dates, lose deposits or 
payments, or disable ATMs. 
</P>
<P>
	A secret New Jersey location offers a peek at the banks'  
contingency plans. These are the unmarked, nondescript offices of 
the New York Clearing House, which settles domestic electronic 
transactions for 950 banks that are headquartered in New York, New 
Jersey, Connecticut and Puerto Rico. The 950 banks represent about 
10 percent of the total number of banks in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate facility in Manhattan, whose location is kept equally  
secret to discourage terrorism, processes international 
transactions for the New York Clearing House. In addition to the 
Clearing House, the Federal Reserve operates regional facilities, 
and two other private operators are located in Arizona and 
California, handling transactions for the rest of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	At the New York Clearing House in New Jersey, 12,000 square feet  
of cavernous rooms are lined with rows of cabinets containing 10 
computers each. They process about 1.5 million electronic transfers 
a day, worth $9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	George Thomas, director of information systems, shows off the  
back-up batteries, diesel generators and telecommunication systems 
that could be deployed within minutes if the front-line systems 
fail. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will probably be some spot outages across the country,''  
Thomas said, ``but we don't foresee any major calamity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adds Andy Kyte, a London-based research director at the Gartner  
Group, an information technology consulting firm: ``The fact is 
that there will be problems. Computer systems have bugs the way 
dogs have fleas. But generally speaking, we still manage to see 
from banks very high service levels and a great willingness to 
rectify problems as they occur. We certainly would cite the banking 
sector as being one of the most prepared sectors of those that we 
monitor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some bank customers apparently still need convincing. About 51  
percent of adults surveyed by the Gallup organization in March said 
they were concerned about Y2K, and almost two-thirds said they 
expect to set aside extra cash before the new year. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrea Kovar is not worried enough to go back to old-fashioned  
paper checks. But she does expect to keep scrupulous account of her 
ATM slips in the final quarter of the year. ``I'm telling you, from 
October on, man, you better save every one you've got,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990711.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 11:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
