<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	India, Pakistan Agree To End Fight  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- The plan to end fighting between  
India and Pakistan in the disputed Kashmir region is easing 
concerns of a wider war between the two nuclear-armed neighbors. 
The plan, agreed to today by top military commanders from India and 
Pakistan, calls for a withdrawal of Islamic guerillas from Kashmir, 
and an end to Indian airstrikes, artillery fire and ground assaults 
in Kashmir's Himalayan peaks. Both nations claim control of 
Kashmir, which both countries border in the north. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran Admits 1 Dead in University Raid  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- The Iranian government  
admitted today that one person, an off-duty soldier, had been shot 
and killed Friday as police and hard-line activists stormed a 
Tehran University dormitory. The raid, which exposed a widening 
gulf between reformists, who support President Mohammad Khatami, 
and conservatives, who control the police and judiciary, prompted 
thousands of students to protest in the strongest expression of 
discontent since the 1979 Islamic revolution. Two security chiefs 
responsible for the raid were fired today. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Denounced for Attack on Smith  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several Republican presidential candidates  
criticized their own party today for attacking conservative Sen. 
Bob Smith, who is expected to quit the GOP and run for president 
under a third party. Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan, both seeking 
the GOP nomination for president in 2000, defended Smith's decision 
to bolt the party and they blamed the GOP for the defection, saying 
the party has abandoned conservative ideas. Both said they would 
remain in the GOP. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Likely To Veto GOP Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will veto legislation GOP  
leaders are promoting that would provide up to $800 billion in tax 
cuts, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today. Summers said 
Clinton would support a $250 billion cut. The GOP alternative, 
Summers said, would threaten ``the progress we've made toward 
paying down debt.'' Democrats and Republicans agree that 
reinforcing Social Security and Medicare should be the top priority 
for most of a projected $2.9 trillion budget surplus over the next 
10 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Pledge To Bring Peace  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister  
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat held their first 
summit today, pledging to rebuild trust and to quickly carry out 
U.S.-brokered accords. Barak pleased the Palestinians by clearly 
acceding to their demand that he unfreeze the U.S.-brokered Wye 
River accords, frozen by Netanyahu within weeks of their signing 
last October. Arafat emphatically promised to contain terror, a 
point of contention with the previous government. 

</P>
<P>
	Changing Dreams May End Trauma  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) -- Altering recurring nightmares may hold  
a key to recovery for many victims of trauma, says Dr. Deidre 
Barrett, a professor of behavioral medicine and hypnotherapy at 
Harvard Medical School. Researchers found that about 100 nightmare 
sufferers were able to decrease the frequency of those dreams by 40 
to 100 percent. Patients were taught to create a new ``dream,'' 
with images they rehearsed daily and thought about before going to 
sleep each night as a way of breaking what for many is a nightmare 
habit. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Investigated King's Successor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Within a month of the assassination of Martin  
Luther King Jr., the FBI began investigating King's successor, 
looking for the same type of ``immoral activities'' the bureau had 
tried to use to discredit King, newly released FBI files show. The 
files, obtained by The Associated Press through the Freedom of 
Information Act, include a memo ordering an investigation of the 
Rev. Ralph David Abernathy. He had been King's right-hand man since 
the two led the Montgomery, Ala., bus boycott in 1955 that launched 
the civil rights movement. 

</P>
