<HEADLINE> Lott Predicts Holbrooke Will Be OKed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott predicted  
Sunday that the Senate will approve Richard Holbrooke as U.S. 
ambassador to the United Nations despite the refusal of Lott and 
three other senators to allow a confirmation vote so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he will'' be confirmed, Lott said on NBC's ``Meet the  
Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's second-ranking Republican senator, Don Nickles of  
Oklahoma, said he too expects a vote to confirm the veteran 
diplomat whose nomination received the unanimous recommendation of 
the Senate Foreign Relations Affairs Committee two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``My guess is we'll eventually get around to a vote, but  
certainly we have the right -- some people have the right -- all 
senators have a right to discuss nominations at length if they 
want,'' Nickles said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``Some people have 
some problems with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate procedures allow members to keep a nomination from the  
floor for unrelated reasons as a pressure tactic against the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., have placed holds, without  
publicly acknowledging them, on the Holbrooke nomination to force 
President Clinton to nominate Bradley A. Smith, a university 
professor from Ohio, to the Federal Election Commission. The other 
holds are by Sens. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, trying to reverse a 
State Department disciplinary action against a former department 
employee at the United Nations; and George Voinovich, R-Ohio, to 
protest Clinton administration policy in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Smith, the Republicans' FEC candidate, who has said  
Clinton's administration is probably the most corrupt in the 
nation's history, Lott seemed not to recall the name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bradley Smith is your candidate ...,'' interviewer Tim Russert  
began. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh. Brad Smith. Right,'' Lott said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, first of all, I think a little too much has been made of  
that,'' Lott said. ``I suspect the nomination of Holbrooke to go to 
the U.N. and be confirmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he couldn't say when, because others also had holds on  
the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., appearing with Nickles on ``Fox News  
Sunday,'' expressed irritation with the holdup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I wanted to say is let's debate these issues in  
the light of the day, not in the back room in our cloakrooms,'' 
Reid said. ``We're the most powerful nation in the world, (and) we 
don't have a representative in the United Nations. That's not 
right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
