<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patients' Bill To Be Debated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate has been talking for more than a  
year about how, when and whether to debate the so-called patients' 
bill of rights. This week, it finally gets down to business. 
</P>
<P>
	But the political posturing and maneuvering that both parties  
have mastered is apt to continue, even as a string of votes on the 
details gets under way today. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans and Democrats have their own legislation labeled a  
patients' bill of rights, though there are major differences 
between them. And each side has political goals it hopes to achieve 
over four days of debate. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Republicans, who enjoy a 55-45 Senate majority, are  
virtually certain to pass the bill they prefer -- one that is more 
limited than the Democrats' plan but still offers many patients 
some new powers in dealing with their health maintenance 
organizations and other managed care plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the way, Democrats will offer as many as 20 amendments --  
each targeting a different piece of the package -- forcing GOP 
senators to support their plan or risk looking like they don't want 
to protect patients. 
</P>
<P>
	The rhetorical lines were clearly drawn as senators offered a  
preview of the debate on the Sunday television talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans argued that the Democratic bill is too expensive and  
will force employers to drop health insurance coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cost of health care would skyrocket and more and more  
people would be dropping their plans. That's not healthy for 
America,'' Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats responded that their bill is not expensive, likening  
it to the cost of a Big Mac -- about $2 a month. They cited 
estimates by the Congressional Budget Office, which said the 
Democratic measure would increase premiums by about 4.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A 4.8 percent jump actually would cost about $9 per month for an  
individual plan and $22 per month for a family plan -- but employers 
usually pick up much of that. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an issue of patients vs. insurance companies,'' Sen.  
Edward Kennedy said on ABC's ``This Week.'' ``It's as simple as 
that. The American people ought to watch this debate and be a part 
of it in this next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a while, Democrats seemed to have the upper hand going into  
the debate. In the Senate, a determined group of senators -- even 
those in the minority party -- can wield enormous power. Democrats 
managed to shut down business until Republicans agreed to a debate 
that would allow them to offer their amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	But the GOP leadership fired back a procedural salvo last week.  
It arranged for the Democratic bill to be the starting point for 
this week's debate. This allows Republicans to talk about what they 
dislike about the Democrats' approach, while making it more 
difficult for Democrats to hammer the GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also makes it more awkward for Democrats to offer their  
amendments, since they will be trying to change their own bill. But 
Democrats plan to do it anyway, simply to get the votes on the 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Near the end of the debate, the GOP will offer the final  
amendment substituting its bill for whatever is on the table. And 
if Republicans hold together, that's what the Senate will pass. 
</P>
<P>
	The only question is whether Democrats pull together a majority  
for any of their individual proposals. If they do, it's possible 
Republicans will feel obliged to include those items in the final 
package. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats are unlikely to win votes on the high-profile  
differences that have received the most attention so far: 
</P>
<P>
	--Democrats want to give patients new rights to sue their HMOs if  
care is denied. Republicans say lawsuits only drive up the cost of 
health care. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kennedy bill is an invitation for lawsuits. You have a  
problem with HMOs, file a lawsuit. We don't think that is the 
answer,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on NBC's ``Meet 
the Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Democrats want to force health insurance companies to cover  
care that doctors believe is ``medically necessary.'' Republicans 
would allow insurers to make those decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Both bills have several provisions giving patients easier  
access to emergency rooms, obstetricians and other specialists. But 
the GOP provisions apply only to 48 million Americans who are in 
federally regulated plans that are exempt from state rules. The 
Democrats want to include everyone who has private insurance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
