<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montgomerie Has Hope in Scotland  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Colin Montgomerie hated the  
reminders: He had never won a title before his adoring fans in 
Scotland and had never won a major. 
</P>
<P>
	He took care of one of those shortcomings Saturday by rallying  
for a three-stroke victory at Loch Lomond. And now, he hopes, that 
elusive first major might just be around the corner at Carnoustie. 
</P>
<P>
	``One gone, one to go, I suppose,'' the 36-year-old Scot said.  
``This is very special to me, coming from this side of Scotland and 
winning here in front of such superb and knowledgeable crowds. The 
support I had was unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomerie looked unbeatable in his final round. He ran off  
nine birdies in 12 holes to make up a four-stroke deficit, 
overtaking eight players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only go into the British Open with confidence and that's  
what many players can't say,'' he said after his third victory of 
the year put him on course to become the leading money winner on 
the PGA European Tour for the seventh straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Monty Magic,'' ``Flying Scot wins in birdie charge,'' and  
``Monty Opens up,'' cried the headlines Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The last home victory at the British Open was by Nick Faldo in  
1992. But Montgomerie knows that a familiar course and a strong 
tuneup do not necessarily bode well for the main event. 
</P>
<P>
	At Troon, two years ago, Montgomerie played the course where his  
father was the secretary. Montgomerie had lived barely 150 yards 
from the first tee and played the course as a youngster. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge galleries followed his opening round and he struggled to a  
76. He followed with good scores of two 69s and a 70, but the 
damage had been done. Montgomerie was a beaten man, and Justin 
Leonard took the title. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year at Royal Birkdale, Montgomerie missed the cut for the  
fifth time. His best British Open finish was a tie for eighth in 
1994 at Turnberry. 
</P>
<P>
	There's another reason to be wary. Montgomerie played target  
golf at tree-lined Loch Lomond, which has been likened to many 
American courses. It is far different from links courses, where the 
sea wind dictates that many shots be played low. 
</P>
<P>
	And then there are the expectations. Montgomerie is Scotland's  
biggest hope to wrest the title from the Americans, who have won 
the title four years in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is savoring his victory at Loch Lomond, and thinks this  
might be his moment. 
</P>
<P>
	``How could I possible feel any better than I do right now,'' he  
said. ``But it's difficult sometimes and I've got to be careful. 
</P>
<P>
	``You tend to think that sometimes the game is easier than it  
is. And you get to Carnoustie and start attacking and you get 
yourself into a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first victory on the Tour was in Portugal in 1989 and I won  
by 11 shots,'' Montgomerie said. ``I thought golf was very easy 
until I got to Valderrama the next week and opened with an 82.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
