<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was fairly steady against the yen early  
Monday amid worry about possible intervention in currency markets 
by Japan's central bank. Japanese stocks fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.38 yen in early trading, down 0.28 yen  
from late Friday in Tokyo but unchanged from its late New York 
level on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 75.03 points,  
or 0.42 percent, to 17,862.70 points in early trading. On Friday, 
the average closed down 29.92 points, or 0.17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was unchanged from Friday's New  
York session in what analysts described as a morning of quiet, 
directionless trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants were cautious about possible yen-selling by  
the Bank of Japan, which has stepped in to prop up the dollar on 
three of the last four Mondays, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial authorities are concerned that a stronger yen  
would slow the country's economic recovery. A stronger yen tends to 
make Japanese exports more expensive abroad and therefore less 
competitive, which cuts into the earnings of export-oriented 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no indication that the Bank of Japan had intervened  
Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 124.52 yen, down  
from 124.97 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices started lower on continued  
profit-taking after recent sharp gains, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei 225 climbed to a 21-month closing high of 18,135.06  
last Monday, but then faced some correction pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 66.81  
points to a new all-time high of 11,193.70 amid expectations of 
robust corporate earnings for the April-June quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 0.02 points, or 0.02 percent, to 1,464.62. The 
TOPIX closed down 4.69 points, or 0.32 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.6350 percent from Friday's finish of 
1.6650 percent, driving its price up 101.43 yen from 101.17 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
