<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Fired Upon in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- American troops in the Kosovo  
international peacekeeping force were fired on in three separate 
incidents yesterday but were not hurt. The shootings underscored 
continuing violence and ethnic tensions one month after KFOR, the 
international peacekeeping force, moved into Kosovo under an 
agreement ridding the province of 40,000 Yugoslav military and 
Serbian police forces. Meanwhile, more Russian troops were flown to 
Kosovo to beef up Moscow's peacekeeping contingent that is to 
comprise 3,600 men by the end of the month. 

</P>
<P>
	Flooding Wreaks Havoc in Serbia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Flooding forced some Serbs to flee  
their homes and left parts of the capital without power yesterday. 
At least one death was reported and 10 people were missing, the 
private Beta news agency said. ``This must be a punishment from 
God. First NATO nearly destroyed everything I had, then this. ... 
Could it be worse?'' said Petko Budimir, 40, whose rented house was 
flooded. His previous home was nearly destroyed when NATO bombed 
Belgrade's Strazevica suburb. The area was a frequent target during 
NATO's 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Wins World Cup Soccer Title  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The U.S. team defeated China 5-4  
yesterday on penalty kicks to capture the Women's World Cup soccer 
title. When Brandi Chastain's left-footed kick landed high in the 
net, the Rose Bowl erupted in cheers. U.S. goalie Briana Scurry had 
stopped Liu Ying's shot with the penalty score at 2-2. The game 
remained 0-0 after regulation and two 15-minute overtime. President 
Clinton was one of the 90,185 spectators at the biggest women's 
sporting event in American history. ``It was the most exciting 
sports event I have ever seen,'' Clinton told the victorious U.S. 
athletes. 

</P>
<P>
	Airdrop to Antarctic Base a Success  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- A U.S. Air Force plane today  
dropped six bundles of medical supplies in near-total darkness at 
the South Pole. The drugs and equipment are needed by an American 
worker there who discovered a lump in her breast but can't leave 
until October, when aircraft can safely land. Commander Lt. Col. 
John Pray called the airdrop ``one of our most challenging 
peacetime missions -- many would argue our most challenging.'' To 
guide the plane to the target, staff at the Amundsen-Scott South 
Pole Station ignited barrels filled with a mixture of combustibles 
and diesel fuel and extinguished all other lights at the base. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Mars Berlin Love Parade  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- An estimated 1.4 million yesterday bounced to the  
techno throb of the Love Parade, the annual all-weekend rave billed 
as the world's largest street party. But the parade was not all 
festive. One person was stabbed to death during a fight, police 
said. Police said they had no suspects, and further details were 
not immediately available. Since the Love Parade started in 1988, 
when a small group danced behind a VW van through then-West Berlin, 
the event has drawn increasingly large crowds -- to the dismay of 
environmentalists. 

</P>
<P>
	NAACP Celebrates 90th Birthday  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP yesterday recommitted itself to  
confronting issues affecting black America. The affirmation came as 
the nation's largest and oldest civil rights organization 
celebrated its 90th birthday on the opening day of a six-day 
convention in New York. ``This convention will be celebratory, but 
we will also be looking back towards the principles we were founded 
on,'' said Julian Bond, the NAACP's national board chairman. ``It's 
nice to reminisce, but we can't afford not to keep looking 
forward.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Three Football Players Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, N.Y. (AP) -- Two New York Jets football players and a  
former Jet were arrested yesterday after an altercation in a Long 
Beach bar and a scuffle with police. Jason Fabini, 24, and John 
``Jumbo'' Elliott, 34, both of the Jets, and Matt O'Dwyer, 26, of 
the Cincinnati Bengals were drinking at Bogart's Bar and Restaurant 
when they became rowdy around 12:30 a.m., said Lt. Joseph Kearnes. 
Police were called and, after requesting assistance from backup 
officers, the three were arrested, Kearnes said. 

</P>
<P>
	Padres Top Rangers 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Eric Owens singled home the tying run with two  
outs in the ninth inning, and the winning run scored on the play 
when Texas reliever John Wetteland missed a throw, lifting the San 
Diego Padres over the Rangers 5-4 yesterday. The tying run scored 
on an infield single, and when Wetteland was late covering the bag 
and given an error for missing Palmeiro's throw, Damian Jackson 
also scored. Wetteland (2-3), trying for his major league-leading 
27th save, blew his fifth save chance. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
