<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Da Silva Tops Capel in 100 Meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Florida track and  
football star John Capel was late out of the blocks Sunday and 
unable to catch Brazil's Andre Domingos Da Silva in the 100-meter 
final at the University Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel, in his first competition outside the United States, was  
rattled by three false starts. On the final one, he ran alone in 
his lane for 50 meters before walking slowly back to the start with 
fists on his hips. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way I can run well is if I start well. No excuses,  
but the false starts kind of got to me,'' said Capel, who won the 
NCAA title in the 200 meters last month in 19.87 seconds, the 
second-fastest time in the world in 1999. ``I knew I had to keep my 
poise, but I just couldn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Da Silva won with a time of 10.34 seconds. Capel finished second  
at 10.35 and South Africa's Matthew Quinn took the bronze in 10.42. 
A strong headwind contributed to the relatively slow times -- 
Capel's best is 10.03. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the slowest I've run all year,'' Capel said. ``I was  
thinking this was going to be a cakewalk. I wasn't on my game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Da Silva was put off by the talk.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Americans are very good at mouthing off,'' the Brazilian  
said. ``I just kept quiet and did what I had to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capel will join Auburn's Coby Miller, who won Friday's 200  
meters, in the 400 relay on Tuesday, the last day of the games. 
Capel passed on the 200, his best event, to prepare for the 100 and 
relay events. 
</P>
<P>
	In men's basketball, the United States moved within one victory  
of its sixth straight gold medal by getting past Spain 88-80 in the 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain trailed 82-80 with 20 seconds left, but Cincinnati forward  
Kenyon Martin and St. John's guard Erick Barkley combined to make 
6-of-6 free throws down the stretch. Martin finished with 22 
points, 11 rebounds and three blocks. Barkley scored 19 points 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia defeated Mexico 85-60 to secure the other spot in  
Monday's final. Yugoslavia was the last country to beat the United 
States at the University Games, in the 1987 gold medal game. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will face Spain in the women's gold medal  
game, also Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In men's volleyball, Germany got past Japan for the gold, with  
Spain beating South Korea for the bronze medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel, 20, has a bright future in sports -- he'll just have to  
pick one. 
</P>
<P>
	He averaged more than 27 yards per return as a kick returner and  
also played wide receiver as a freshman last season at No. 5 
Florida. Football practice starts the day after he returns to the 
United States from the Spanish island of Mallorca. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he turned on the jets and nearly caught Silva.  
</P>
<P>
	``I saw Silva out of the corner of my eye with about 30 meters  
left,'' he said. ``I kicked it up, but just couldn't get him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, getting second place means you're the first loser,'' he  
added. ``You have to take losses, but I don't like them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olena Govorova defended her 1997 title in the triple jump with  
the year's best leap of 49 feet, 2 1/4 inches, which also shattered 
her own University Games record. 
</P>
<P>
	Angela Williams, the NCAA champion from Southern California, won  
the women's dash in 11.19 seconds, holding off a late-charging 
Katia Benth of France. Benth was second in 11.25, with Cuba's 
Virgen Benavides third at 11.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Andria King and Yolanda McCray gave the United States gold and  
silver in the women's 100 hurdles, Poland's Ewa Ryback won the 
women's javelin, and Elena Buhaianu of Romania took the 1,500 
meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Men's winners included Italy's Giuseppe Maffei in the 3,000  
steeplechase, Richard Spiegelburg of Germany in the pole vault, and 
defending champion Norberto Tellez of Cuba in the 800. 
</P>
<P>
	In tennis, South Korea's Hyung Lee upset top-seeded Albert  
Portas of Spain 6-4, 6-1, 3-6, 6-3 to win the men's title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
