<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fossett Leads Mackinac Yacht Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MACKINAC ISLAND, Mich. (AP) -- Millionaire Steve Fossett's Stars  
and Stripes led the pack sailing toward the halfway point Sunday in 
the Chicago-to-Mackinac yacht race. 
</P>
<P>
	Most ships were expected to finish the course Monday. The race's  
winners will then be determined based on a system of handicaps 
based on each boat's speed potential. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars and Stripes, a 60-foot Morrelli catamaran piloted by  
Fossett, was expected to finish the course late Sunday night. 
Fossett, who failed his second attempt to fly around the world in a 
balloon last year, holds the course record in the open division. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a slow, steady and safe race,'' said Penny Beatty,  
spokeswoman for the Race to Mackinac. ``Unless wind conditions 
alter, it is not foreseeable that he will break that record. This 
is not going to be a record-setting year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Ludde Ingvall RX-Sight was spotted an hour behind Stars  
and Stripes. His boat won in the IMS (international measurement 
system) division last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 333-mile race began at 1 p.m. EDT Saturday in Chicago with  
winds at 20 to 25 knots out of the north to northeast, forcing 
boats to continually turn to fill the sails in 6-foot seas. 
According to Beatty, the winds Sunday had calmed to 6 to 8 knots 
out of the southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	``The direction of the wind is more favorable but the speed of  
the wind has dropped,'' Beatty said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of the 273 starters had dropped out for mechanical reasons  
by Sunday afternoon, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the 92nd running of this invitation-only race are a  
varied group of sailors and vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngest sailor is 12-years-old and the oldest is 82. The  
sailboats range in size from 27 feet to 80 feet with the average 
crew size being eight to 12 sailors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our fleet is very diverse,'' Beatty said. ``We have several  
boats sailing with several generations. There's lots of tradition, 
lots of families who enter this race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rock singer Bob Seger is also racing. Seger's boat was spotted  
in the second group behind the leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's doing actually very well,'' Beatty said. ``He's  
definitely in a good pack.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
