<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dry Kentucky Creates Hay Hotline / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Faced with intense heat and little rainfall, many farmers in  
central and eastern Kentucky are selling their cattle because they 
can't feed them. 
</P>
<P>
	``There isn't a bit of moisture,'' said Darrell Arrington, a  
Lawrence County farmer, who with his father, Kenneth, sold nearly 
40 head of cattle because there was no water or pasture land for 
the animals. 
</P>
<P>
	To combat the problem, the Kentucky Department of Agriculture  
established a toll-free hay hotline last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hotline is to hook up people who do have hay with the ones  
who don't,'' said Sally Wilson, a department spokeswoman. ``If 
people need it they can call, or if people have it then they can 
call in also and we'll keep track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainfall since April 1 has been four to six inches below normal  
in much of eastern Kentucky and two to four inches short in parts 
of central and south-central Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said farmers in some counties are faced with little  
pastureland and are turning to what hay they have to feed the 
livestock. When winter comes, there may be no hay left. 
</P>
<P>
	In western Kentucky, however, rainfall amounts are two inches  
above normal since April 1. Wilson said officials hope that farmers 
in areas not facing a drought will contribute hay. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrington said that if the problems subside, he'd like to buy  
some more livestock. ``We haven't had any rain in ... I don't know 
how long it's been. Everything's drying up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Republic County farmer James Pachta parked  
his combine in the shed last Thursday night and climbed out of the 
cab with the satisfaction that comes at the end of another 
successful wheat harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	The next morning, he drove to Linn in neighboring Washington  
County to work at his off-farm job -- branch president of Peoples 
State Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a dual role that has given Pachta a special empathy to the  
problems in the farm economy as the 1999 Kansas wheat harvest winds 
down, with wheat prices hovering at $2.16 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pachta was especially glad when he saw yields in the area coming  
in at 60 pounds per bushel to offset the decline in prices -- and 
why he was anxious when unrelenting rains delayed the harvest 
around the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was nervous about my borrowers and hoping they got their  
wheat crop in and I was nervous about my crop,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His bank tries to go the extra mile with farmers who have dealt  
with them for years, especially in these times of low prices for 
most farm commodities. But banking regulators do not look at 
borrowers' loan history. 
</P>
<P>
	``The regulatory people have perceived there is some kind of ag  
crisis out there, then when they come to look at the loan they tend 
to look at it harder,'' Pachta said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said banking regulators have been ingrained to think there is  
a farm crisis, and they are coming into banks carrying a ``heavier 
stick'' when examining farm loans. 
</P>
<P>
	His own bank tightened its lending policies a couple of years  
ago and now documents things a little closer, makes sure the loans 
are covered by crop insurance and is careful not to lend more than 
the insurance value on the crop, Pachta said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
