<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Open Dream Ends for Dougherty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Ed Dougherty blew the lead Sunday  
in the final round of the U.S. Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he insisted he was happy to be runner-up, and it was easy  
to see he was telling the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I need any condolences,'' Dougherty said on the  
18th green. ``But thanks for the congratulations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He ended up with a final-round 72 and was 4-under 284 for the  
tournament, three strokes behind champion Dave Eichelberger. 
</P>
<P>
	All week, Dougherty said he liked being called a dreamer. The  
fans loved his blue-collar background, the scrambler who won once 
during his on-again, off-again 23-year stint on the PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Dougherty isn't exactly the glamor boy of the Senior Tour. He  
has a body like the Michelin man and he lumbers up the fairways. 
His bright blue shirt was already soaked with sweat on the first 
tee Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was going great for Dougherty when he birdied the fourth and  
seventh to reach 6-under, then he took it to 7-under with another 
birdie at No. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	But his wake-up buzzer was a double-bogey on the 160-yard par-3  
14th, where he came to the tee tied with Eichelberger. Dougherty 
swept the ball with an 8-iron and knew right away he was in 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I put a lot of backspin on it,'' he said. ``Didn't hit  
it solid enough to carry up there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It rolled into a well under the flag and finally stopped on the  
fringe. He pitched up to the plateau where the pin rested, leaving 
him with a sloping 8-footer for par. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed, curling the ball short by more than a foot. Then his  
3-footer lipped all the way around the cup and stayed out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it went in, but it did more than a 360,'' he said.  
``I really didn't know where that would end up. It did like a 420 
or something. It went all the way around the hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moments earlier, a roar came up from the gallery on the 15th,  
where Eichelberger, playing in the next-to-last group, was on his 
way to the title after a birdie carried him to 8-under. 
</P>
<P>
	Dougherty said he never looked at the leader board, but he knew  
he had to do something. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to get some birdies right there,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	There wouldn't be any. In fact, he bogeyed the 17th with a  
three-putt after finding himself on the back fringe. After his 
tap-in, he pulled out his notebook to study the 18th, but the look 
in his eyes suggested he knew it was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I was playing for second place,'' he recalled. ``It's  
a great thing to say, but it's a terrible situation to be in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dougherty received a resounding cheer when he walked up to the  
18th green. He parred the hole after getting a 60-foot putt to 8 
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Dougherty said afterward he needed no sympathy. He has  
been a grinder all his life, whether taking the point for his 
infantry unit in Vietnam or working in a bag shop for $1.50 an hour 
on his hometown golf course in Linwood, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a good time all week,'' Dougherty said. ``There are  
plenty of people out there on the driving ranges across America, 
pretending to hit a shot in the U.S. Open. I just lived that 
dream.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990711.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 10:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Thrilled About Soccer Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. women's victory in the World Cup was  
more than just another match, it was a watershed event for women 
everywhere. At least that's how soccer's newest convert -- President 
Clinton -- sees it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the most exciting sports event that I believe I have  
ever seen,'' Clinton told the American team after its victory 
Saturday over China in a shootout following a 0-0 tie at the Rose 
Bowl in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The players, clad in yellow championship T-shirts crowded around  
the president, hugging him and cheering. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a triumphant end to a long week for Clinton, who extended  
a four-day tour through some of the nation's most impoverished 
communities to remain on the West Coast for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton called the U.S. women's victory -- in a match that went  
to double overtime before being decided on penalty kicks -- a lesson 
in ``courage and endurance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an amazing day,'' he said. ``We learned a lot today  
about soccer and about women athletes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An avid golfer and football and basketball fan, Clinton admitted  
that he did not know much about soccer, which he first was exposed 
to when daughter Chelsea took up the game at age 6. 
</P>
<P>
	But he could not stop talking about the drama of the game aboard  
Air Force One before leaving Los Angeles for Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``It went on forever and you could never tell who was going to  
win,'' he said. ``It was just amazing. The momentum would shift and 
then shift back and then shift back. They were all so great, if I 
we're not a partisan, you almost hate to see either side lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that a vast television audience watched the match around  
the globe, Clinton agreed it was a watershed event for women's 
sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this will mobilize -- I think you'll have more young  
girls playing soccer,'' he said. ``I think you'll have more young 
girls playing other sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the drive and staying power the women showed was an  
important lesson on why women deserve equal opportunities. He 
called the championship ``a tribute to Title IX,'' the federal code 
requiring schools to provide women athletes the same resources for 
sports that men receive, with helping 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you'll have even more young girls, you know, finding  
self-confidence, other ways to express themselves because of what 
these women have accomplished,'' Clinton said. ``And I would expect 
that it would have that impact in other countries as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also visited the losing team's locker room after the  
match, expressing his appreciation for China's performance in the 
World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The interesting thing was the Chinese women were very upbeat,  
very proud of their performance, very respectful of the American 
team.'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations with Beijing have been strained since NATO mistakenly  
bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade during the air campaign over 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese players were visibly delighted to see the president  
of the United States. Members of the squad videotaped Clinton as he 
spoke to them and posed with him for pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very impressed by those women. How can you not be?'' he  
said. ``No one played harder than they did. And yet they bore their 
last minute defeat with enormous dignity and grace.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
