<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's population likely will increase by  
30 percent over the next 30 years and the country will have to 
prepare to care for a growing portion of elderly, government 
agencies reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Mexicans is expected to grow from 100 million in  
2000 to 130 million by 2030, the government news agency Notimex 
reported, citing studies by two state offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of people older than 65 years will grow from 4.4  
million as of 1998 to 6.8 million in 2010 and 15.6 million in 2030, 
the National Population Council said. 
</P>
<P>
	This change will require the government to allocate more  
resources toward the social security system, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1970s, the average birthrate has fallen from seven  
children to two-and-a-half. Life-expectancy, meanwhile, has reached 
nearly 74 years -- more than doubling the 35 years which was the 
average in 1930. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's president said Sunday he  
is recalling the country's ambassador to Colombia because of 
allegedly insulting comments made by Colombia's trade minister. 
</P>
<P>
	President Hugo Chavez said ambassador Fernando Gerbasi was  
ordered to return immediately to Caracas for consultations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian minister, Martha Lucia Ramirez, last week  
criticized a Venezuelan law requiring Colombian truck drivers to 
hand their cargo over to Venezuelan drivers at the border. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the Caracas daily El Nacional, she said  
Chavez ``talks about integration, but the measures applied by some 
of his officials are just the opposite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez shot back on his weekly radio call-in show Sunday, saying  
Ramirez ``made some statements that showed a lack of respect for 
the government and the people Venezuela.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP) -- The bodies of two men who were shot  
several times in the head have been found in western Mexico, 
apparently the latest cases in a wave of suspected drug-related 
killings in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were found Saturday near Tecpan de Galeana, 50 miles  
northwest of the resort of Acapulco. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last two months, police in the region of Guerrero state  
believe seven other men were killed in drug trafficking disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's government wants tighter  
controls on so-called social groups working in the Amazon, fearing 
some aim to plunder the rainforest's natural resources, a newspaper 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the non-governmental groups which carry out social  
studies and research in the region are bona-fide but some have 
``other objectives,'' said Defense Minister Elcio Alvares in an 
interview with Rio daily Jornal Do Brasil. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Federal Police chief for the Amazon, Mauro Sposito,  
claimed in the daily that some groups are acting unofficially on 
behalf of multinational companies keen to locate valuable 
resources. 
</P>
<P>
	There are some 1,000 non-governmental groups in Brazil. At least  
300 work in the Amazon region. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's president said Sunday his  
government will fully cooperate with an investigation into 1989 
riots in which security forces killed hundreds of people. 
</P>
<P>
	``My government does not have any intention to hide the truth,''  
President Hugo Chavez told The Associated Press. Authorities should 
``establish who is responsible ... and carry out justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights workers charge that security forces put down the  
February 1989 riots by indiscriminately spraying mountainside slums 
with bullets even after widespread looting over soaring bus fares 
and food prices had ended. 
</P>
<P>
	They say dozens of shooting victims were dumped in a mass grave  
and have never been identified or turned over to their families. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyer Raul Arrieta denies widespread human rights  
violations took place and says security forces were simply 
restoring order in a chaotic situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Officially, 276 people were killed in the riots though rights  
activists say the number is 400 or more. Few soldiers or police 
have gone to jail for the killings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
