<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsinite Kelly Denied at GMO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- On the biggest day of his golfing life, Jerry  
Kelly only lost his focus briefly. 
</P>
<P>
	It was still too long.  
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in four years, the Madison native had a  
chance to win the Greater Milwaukee Open in the final round. But 
just as Loren Roberts did in a 1996 playoff, Carlos Franco stole 
the title from Kelly. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly admits he desperately wants to win the only PGA Tour event  
in his home state. After sleeping on a lead for the first time in 
his four-year career, he thought a win Sunday was his destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a very good chance today, but I let it slip away in the  
middle of the round,'' he sighed afterward. ``I can see plain as 
day what went wrong and where it slipped away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly entered the day with a chance at capturing both the GMO  
and a slice of history. He held a one-stroke lead over Franco after 
54 holes, all of which Kelly had played without a bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	He stretched his bogeyless streak to 59 holes on Sunday before  
the tricky par-5 sixth hole, where he three-putted for a 6. Just 
like that, his chance at a perfect tournament was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	And so was his lead. Franco birdied the hole to match him at 17  
under, and Kelly began to tense up. The pressure of a cheering 
gallery and Franco's steady play caught up to him, and he bogeyed 
four of the next five holes. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I made the first bogey, I said, 'So what? That  
happens,''' Kelly said. ``Then I lost control of my game ... and by 
the time I got it back, it was too late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly was down but not out. He chipped in on No. 14 with a  
brilliant sand wedge shot, which he celebrated by bowing to the 
roaring crowd and high-fiving his caddy. The shot brought him 
within three strokes of Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	A bogey on 16, however, put him too far back to recover. Tom  
Lehman birdied No. 18 and Kelly missed a chance at his second-best 
career finish when he missed a makable putt on the final green and 
allowed Lehman to slip in front of him for second place. 
</P>
<P>
	When the final shot slid past the cup, Kelly flopped onto his  
back, and the crowd both groaned and laughed. They then gave their 
native son and Franco a standing ovation as they congratulated each 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Wisconsinite Steve Stricker was thought before the  
tournament to be the Badger State's best chance at a homegrown 
champion, considering his outstanding season and his runner-up 
finish last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kelly, a former hockey player, endeared himself to fans with  
his exaggerated gestures and running commentary on his game. 
</P>
<P>
	On the 17th hole, he hit a 150-yard iron directly at the pin.  
But when he followed the shot with a Carlton Fisk-like dance and a 
chant of ``Oh, please go in. Oh, please go in,'' he sounded just 
like any weekend warrior with a double-digit handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	As he did in 1996, Kelly plans to take the frustrations of his  
loss and channel them into improving his play for the rest of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I probably learned more today about myself than I have in any  
other event,'' Kelly said. ``There were a lot more nerves for me 
today. I saw exactly when I got out of my game plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this had happened to me earlier in my career, I would've  
gone out the next week and played steamed, played the next 
tournament like it owed me something. ... I'm going to learn from 
this and get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he was asked if he thinks he'll ever win the tournament he  
wants so badly, Kelly was unequivocal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, I'll come back and win it next year,'' he said with a  
grin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
