<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mealybug Might Threaten U.S. Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- The two passengers  
carrying basil and plant cuttings aboard flights from St. Thomas to 
Miami last year were unsuspecting carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	So were 14 others who sent packages or traveled from six other  
Caribbean islands to Florida, where port inspectors discovered the 
hitchhiking pink hibiscus mealybug. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a pest that has eaten its way through millions of dollars  
in crops and ornamental plants across the Caribbean since it first 
was reported in the Western Hemisphere, in Grenada in 1994. By June 
1997 it had reached the U.S. Virgin Islands and, a year later, 
Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're watching the ports, but these things have a way of  
getting in,'' said Kenneth Vick of the U.S. Department of 
Agriculture's research service in Beltsville, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	With Miami at the hub of U.S. commerce for Latin America,  
Florida agriculture officials say it's just a matter of time before 
up to 17 Southern states could be infected. 
</P>
<P>
	The bugs feed on the sap, roots and leaves of more than 200  
plants, from oranges and squash to bougainvillea, injecting a 
killer toxin from their saliva. They are tiny -- the oval-shaped, 
wingless female about 1/8 inch and a pink-red, the male half that 
size and a rusty red with wings. And they propagate rapidly, since 
the female lays up to 600 eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Agricultural economist Joe Moffitt, of the University of  
Massachusetts, has predicted that if the mainland is infiltrated 
there could be $750 million a year in losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we find is the mealybug is moving and isn't detected in  
these other countries until it's a blowout situation,'' said 
mealybug expert Dale Meyerdirk, a USDA entomologist in Riverdale, 
Md. 
</P>
<P>
	The pink mealybug was already established in Asia, Africa and  
Australia when it reached Grenada and, the following year, 
Trinidad. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Caribbean countries responded with massive doses of  
pesticides, but those could not penetrate the female mealybug's 
waxy coating. The two countries then turned to slashing and 
burning, which began denuding vast areas with no pest relief. 
</P>
<P>
	As the pest pushed farther north, U.S. officials hurried to find  
a way to arrest it. Their hope was a wasp. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1997, Meyerdirk set up a breeding program in the U.S.  
Virgin Islands for stingless wasps that lay eggs in the mealybug. 
When the eggs hatch, they devour the pest's innards. 
</P>
<P>
	The program has grown tens of thousands of the wasps and  
supplied them free to anyone, from backyard gardeners to hoteliers 
to agriculture ministries. It is credited with suppressing the 
mealybug in the northern reaches of the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	But that may not be enough.  
</P>
<P>
	The pest has reached Guyana, the only affected South American  
country, and hopped up the archipelago across more than 25 
Caribbean islands. 
</P>
<P>
	In Trinidad, it attacked 130 types of plants and crops. Losses  
could exceed an annual $125 million, or 2.3 percent of gross 
domestic product, the Inter-American Institute for Cooperation on 
Agriculture reports. 
</P>
<P>
	By next year, it projects that Cuba, Jamaica, the Dominican  
Republic and Haiti will be infested. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next five years, the Costa Rica-based institute says, the  
pest is expected to travel north, to the southern United States, 
and as far south as Brazil, Colombia and Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	Many islands still are suffering trade embargoes, though  
recently pest-free countries such as Barbados have sent inspectors 
to identify mealybug-free areas and certify their produce for 
export. 
</P>
<P>
	Haiti and the Dominican Republic regularly send Meyerdirk  
suspect specimens but thus far remain free of the pink mealybug, he 
said. Also clear are the Bahamas and Cayman Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyerdirk says that if the $250,000-a-year USDA project folded  
today, the wasps would control 92-95 percent of the bugs on treated 
islands. 
</P>
<P>
	In Puerto Rico, the wasps have reduced the number of pests by  
more than 88 percent, preventing the losses that hit other islands. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Florida, nursery plants require 100 percent control and  
any infestation could bring embargoes by the European Union and 
other U.S. states, hurting the $1.46 billion nursery industry. 
</P>
<P>
	For six months, scientists in Hawaii have been studying  
irradiation and heat treatments and soon will include chemical 
drenches and dips. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we have this pest that other states feel threatened by and  
we don't have a treatment that can be applied, we have a real 
economic disaster in the making,'' said Mike Shannon of the USDA, 
who oversees port inspection in Florida. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
