<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	2 Arrested in U.S. Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Police arrested two men Sunday for allegedly  
conspiring with Osama bin Laden in last summer's deadly bombings of 
two U.S. embassies in Africa, authorities said. They are charged 
with conspiring with bin Laden and his network to murder American 
citizens on or prior to Aug. 8, 1998, police said. Ibrahim Hussein 
Abdel Hadi Eidarous, 42, and Adel Mohanned Abdul Almagid Bary are 
scheduled to appear Monday at Bow Street Magistrates Court for the 
start of the extradition process. Bin Laden is suspected of 
masterminding and financing the Aug. 7, 1998 bombings of the 
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania which killed 224 people and wounded 
thousands. 

</P>
<P>
	India, Pakistan Agree to Kashmir Pullout  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Top military commanders from India  
and Pakistan agreed Sunday to the withdrawal of Islamic militants 
from Kashmir, easing fears of a wider war between the two 
nuclear-armed neighbors. The plan calls for Pakistani-backed 
fighters to withdraw from the Indian-controlled region and for both 
sides to halt airstrikes, artillery fire and ground assaults. 
Kashmir is split between India and Pakistan, and was divided by the 
Line of Control under an agreement signed in 1972. 

</P>
<P>
	Iranians Rally in United States  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iranians across the United  
States staged rallies in several major cities Sunday in a show of 
support for student uprisings in Iran. Rallies occurred in Los 
Angeles, New York, Dallas and Washington. A police raid Friday on a 
Tehran University dormitory prompted thousands of students to 
protest in the strongest expression of discontent since the 1979 
Islamic revolution. The demonstrations expose a widening gulf 
between reformists, who support President Mohammad Khatami, and 
conservatives, who control the police and judiciary. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Says Wife's a Bigger Story  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says that while issues like  
health-care reform are important, his wife's likely run for the 
Senate from New York is a better story. ``She's a better story,'' 
Clinton said in an interview with New York Times columnist Bob 
Herbert. But, Clinton added, ``this is an important story, what 
we've been doing these last three days. I'm so thrilled. I hope I 
can persuade them to adopt the legislation by the end of the 
year.'' The president made his remarks during his recent trip to 
California to promote his ideas for changing the Medicare program. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Pledge Peace at Summit  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister  
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat promised Sunday to 
bring peace by rebuilding trust and quickly carrying out 
U.S.-brokered accords. Barak pleased the Palestinians by clearly 
acceding to their demand that he implement the U.S.-brokered Wye 
River accords, frozen by Netanyahu within weeks of their signing 
last October. Arafat emphatically promised to contain terror, a 
point of contention with the previous government. 

</P>
<P>
	Probe of Cuban Migrant's Death Urged  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Anti-Castro groups repeated calls Sunday for  
officials to investigate a collision at sea involving a Coast Guard 
cutter that resulted in the death of a Cuban migrant. Officials say 
the refugee boat was trying to evade capture when it collided with 
the cutter and sank. The Cuban-American National Foundation says 
the incident needs to be reviewed because the Coast Guard's 
intercept policy is putting lives in peril. Under U.S. policy, 
foreigners who reach U.S. shores are allowed to seek asylum, but 
those intercepted at sea are returned to their homeland or another 
country. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell in early trading Monday amid  
worry about possible intervention in currency markets by Japan's 
central bank. The Nikkei dropped 75.03 to 17,862.70. In New York 
Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 66.81 points to a new 
all-time high of 11,193.70 amid expectations of robust corporate 
earnings for the April-June quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs Defeat White Sox 6-3  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Steve Trachsel won for the first time in nearly  
two months as the Cubs beat the White Sox 6-3 Sunday night, taking 
two of three games from their Chicago rivals at Comiskey Park. 
After losing their first four games against the White Sox this 
season, including three straight last month at Wrigley Field, the 
veteran Cubs regrouped and captured the final two at raucous 
Comiskey, where fans waved towels and got into several fights. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
</P>
