<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	India, Pakistan Agree To End Fight  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Top military commanders from India  
and Pakistan agreed today on a plan to end the fighting in 
India-controlled Kashmir, easing concerns of a wider war between 
the two nuclear-armed neighbors. The plan calls for a withdrawal of 
Islamic guerillas from the region, and an end to Indian airstrikes, 
artillery fire and ground assaults in Kashmir's Himalayan peaks. 
India accuses Pakistan of orchestrating the occupation of Himalayan 
peaks on the Indian side of a 1972 cease-fire line, and charges 
that Pakistan has sent its own soldiers and Afghan mercenaries 
across the line. 

</P>
<P>
	Congo Rebels Vow To Continue Fight  
</P>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Congolese rebels vowed today to keep  
fighting despite the signing of a peace accord to end Africa's 
biggest ongoing war. The accord was signed late yesterday by 
Congolese President Laurent Kabila, the target of the 11-month old 
rebel campaign, along with his foreign military allies and the 
countries that have backed the rebels, Uganda and Rwanda. One of 
the major accomplishments of the peace accord was to assure Rwanda 
that ethnic Hutu militiamen implicated in the 1994 genocide in that 
country and hiding across the border in Congo would be located and 
handed over to an international war crimes tribunal. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Fired Upon in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. peacekeeping forces came under  
fire several times over the weekend in Kosovo, evidence that 
tensions are still simmering in the war-torn Serbian province. No 
Americans were hurt in the shootings yesterday in southeastern 
Kosovo, but U.S. soldiers believe they shot and killed one 
assailant and seriously wounded another, U.S. Capt. Paul Swiergosz 
said. Meanwhile, Russian troops faced a protest Sunday by ethnic 
Albanians who distrust them and from Italian peacekeepers who 
refused to let them through a checkpoint. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Pledge To Bring Peace  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister  
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat pledged today to 
speed the implementation of U.S.-brokered peace accords. ``Both 
sides have suffered enough,'' Barak said. ``I reiterate my 
commitment that we will work jointly as partners to implement the 
peace of the brave,'' Arafat said. Barak pleased the Palestinians 
by unfreezing the U.S.-brokered Wye River accords. Arafat 
emphatically promised to contain terrorism, a point of contention 
with the previous government. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Likely To Veto GOP Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will veto legislation GOP  
leaders are promoting that would provide up to $800 billion in tax 
cuts, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today. He said 
Clinton would support a $250 billion cut. The GOP alternative, 
Summers said, would threaten ``the progress we've made toward 
paying down debt ... would put at risk core government, everything 
from the national parks to the FBI to medical research.'' Summers 
succeeded Robert Rubin on July 2. 

</P>
<P>
	Hackers Launch New Invasion Tool  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Computer security companies updated their  
virus-detection software today after the launch at a hackers 
convention of a new tool designed for stealth invasions of networks 
operated by Microsoft Windows. The tool's authors, an irreverent 
group named Cult of the Dead Cow, or CDC, and other hackers 
attending the seventh annual ``DefCon'' convention in Las Vegas 
charged that Microsoft has refused to address gaping security holes 
in Windows. By exploiting those vulnerabilities, hackers hope to 
force the world's largest software company to repair them. 

</P>
<P>
	'American Pie' Leads Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The raunchy teen comedy ``American Pie''  
topped the box office over the weekend, bringing in $18.1 million. 
The movie, about a bunch of high school guys trying to lose their 
virginity by graduation, knocked Will Smith's critically savaged 
``Wild Wild West'' into second place, while ``Arlington Road,'' the 
only other movie opening in wide release, debuted with a 
disappointing $7.4 million, industry estimates showed today. ``Wild 
Wild West'' lost a devastating 40 percent of its audience after two 
weeks, earning $16.7 million for a total of $76.4 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves' Maddux Wins Fourth Straight  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Greg Maddux won his fourth straight decision and  
Ryan Klesko homered twice, leading the Atlanta Braves over the 
Boston Red Sox 8-1 today. Maddux (10-5) allowed one run and six 
hits in eight innings. In his last five starts, the four-time Cy 
Young Award winner has allowed three earned runs in 35 2-3 innings 
(a 0.76 ERA), dropping his season ERA from 4.64 to 3.40. Boston 
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, voted to start Tuesday's All-Star game 
at Fenway Park, missed his ninth straight game because of a 
strained groin but said he'll be able to play Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
