<HEADLINE> Taylor Honored for AIDS Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Elizabeth Taylor was honored for  
her longtime support of Project Angel Food, a meal-delivery program 
that serves homebound AIDS patients. 
</P>
<P>
	She received an Angel Award Saturday night at the organization's  
10th anniversary celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about hope, kindness and a connection with one  
another,'' Taylor told the audience, which included actresses 
Shirley MacLaine and Camryn Manheim and singer Barry Manilow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elizabeth Taylor is simply the finest choice to receive this  
award,'' said John Gile, project director. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only has she been supporting Project Angel Food since day  
one, but she has also led the way around the world to break down 
barriers in the fight against AIDS,'' Gile said. ``We just love 
her, and this is our way of saying thanks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past decade, the program has served more than 7,000  
individuals with HIV or AIDS. They receive meals prepared by 
professional chefs and volunteer assistants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
