<DOCNO> APW19990711.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 15:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh Coke Stacks Destroyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A demolition crew on Sunday toppled six coke  
stacks along the Monongahela River, long-time symbols of this 
city's industrial heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	The destruction of the stacks of LTV Corp.'s now-closed coke  
plant signals an end to the days when steel mills and industrial 
plants choked the banks of the city's three rivers, drawing people 
-- many of them immigrants -- to work and live in the communities 
that sprang up there. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke is coal heated in an oven to remove the gasses; it burns  
with intense heat and is used in the steel-making process. 
</P>
<P>
	The first five stacks went easily, 15 pounds of explosives  
weakened the base of each. The sixth stack held on, gasping a cloud 
of smoke from its top but standing firm in denial. Workers rounded 
up more explosives and finally knocked it over late in the 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's just that people don't like to see part of their  
history go,'' said Tom Berkins, who grew up in Hazelwood, a 
Pittsburgh neighborhood in the shadow of the stacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkins, 44, now lives in Oakland, Calif., and works as an  
environmental engineer. His father worked in the steel industry and 
Berkins remembers looking out his bedroom window to see smoke 
belching from the stacks -- the thick sulfur smell creeping into his 
nose. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, he has returned to Pittsburgh to visit his  
parents and watched as the steel mills fell one by one. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's clean air and clean water, but it's taken its toll on  
the economy. The steel mills obviously were the lifeblood of this 
area.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990711.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Congo Rebels Vow To Keep Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Defiant Congolese rebels pledged today to  
keep fighting despite the signing of an accord to end Africa's 
biggest ongoing war. The accord was signed late yesterday by 
Congolese President Laurent Kabila, the target of the 11-month old 
rebel campaign, along with his foreign military allies and the 
countries that have backed the rebels, Uganda and Rwanda. The 
signers agreed to stop fighting and form a joint military 
commission and start disarming independent militias. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Pledge Peace at Summit  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister  
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat promised today to 
bring peace by rebuilding trust and quickly carrying out 
U.S.-brokered accords. Barak pleased the Palestinians by clearly 
acceding to their demand that he implement the U.S.-brokered Wye 
River accords, frozen by Netanyahu within weeks of their signing 
last October. Arafat emphatically promised to contain terror, a 
point of contention with the previous government. 

</P>
<P>
	India, Pakistan To End Kashmir Fight  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- A plan to end fighting between  
India and Pakistan in the disputed Kashmir region is easing 
concerns of a wider war between the two nuclear-armed neighbors. 
The plan calls for a withdrawal of Islamic guerillas from Kashmir, 
and an end to Indian airstrikes, artillery fire and ground assaults 
in Kashmir's Himalayan peaks. Both nations claim control of 
Kashmir, which both countries border in the north. 

</P>
<P>
	NAACP To Sue Gun Industry  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP will sue handgun manufacturers,  
distributors and importers, hoping that new restrictions in the 
ways firearms are marketed and sold will help keep guns from 
criminals, sources said today. Sources within the National 
Association for the Advancement of Colored People told The 
Associated Press that a formal announcement of the suit will come 
tomorrow. The move would put the civil rights group in league with 
cities like New Orleans, Chicago, Cleveland and Boston which have 
sued the firearms industry in hopes of curbing street and school 
yard violence. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices Jump Nearly 2 Cents  
</P>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- Gasoline prices jumped nearly 2 cents  
in the past two weeks because of rising crude oil prices and 
increased demand, an industry analyst said today. The national 
weighted average, including all grades and taxes, was $1.2153 
Friday, up 1.93 cents a gallon from the previous survey on June 25, 
said Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the Lundberg Survey of 10,000 
gas stations nationwide. A main factor has been more expensive 
crude oil, which has risen from $13 a barrel at the beginning of 
the year to $20 now. 

</P>
<P>
	Nev. Battles 50,000-Acre Wildfire  
</P>
<P>
	MIDAS, Nev. (AP) -- High humidity and calmer winds today helped  
firefighters in their battle against a wildfire that has consumed 
more than 50,000 acres of dry brush. Despite the progress, fire 
officials said don't expect to contain the blaze until Wednesday. 
``It's one of the biggest wildfires in the West so far this 
summer,'' fire information officer Nick Zufelt said. Investigators 
had not determined the cause of the fire, which began Thursday, but 
they believe it was started by man. 

</P>
<P>
	Hackers Launch New Invasion Tool  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Computer security companies updated their  
virus-detection software today after the launch at a hackers 
convention of a new tool designed for stealth invasions of networks 
operated by Microsoft Windows. The tool's authors, an irreverent 
group named Cult of the Dead Cow, or CDC, and other hackers 
attending the seventh annual ``DefCon'' convention in Las Vegas 
charged that Microsoft has refused to address gaping security holes 
in Windows. By exploiting those vulnerabilities, hackers hope to 
force the world's largest software company to repair them. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell in early trading Monday amid  
worry about possible intervention in currency markets by Japan's 
central bank. The Nikkei dropped 75.03 to 17,862.70. In New York 
Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 66.81 points to a new 
all-time high of 11,193.70 amid expectations of robust corporate 
earnings for the April-June quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Bottenfield Wins 14th for Cards  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Kent Bottenfield pitched six innings to  
become the National League's first 14-game winner as the St. Louis 
Cardinals beat the San Francisco Giants 5-4 today to avoid a 
three-game sweep. J.D. Drew's two-run homer began the scoring in a 
five-run first inning. Fernando Tatis and Edgar Renteria added RBI 
doubles and Darren Bragg had a run-scoring single in the inning. 
Bottenfield (14-3) became the first St. Louis pitcher since Joaquin 
Andujar in 1985 to win 14 games before the All-Star break. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
