<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Wife's a Bigger Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says that while issues like  
health-care reform are important, his wife's likely run for the 
Senate from New York is a better story. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a better story,'' Clinton said in an interview with New  
York Times columnist Bob Herbert. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Clinton added, ``this is an important story, what we've  
been doing these last three days. I'm so thrilled. I hope I can 
persuade them to adopt the legislation by the end of the year ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president made his remarks during his recent trip to  
California to promote his ideas for changing the Medicare program, 
including ways to help older Americans pay for drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also said he'd be happy to live in New York after  
he leaves the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to divide my time between New York and Arkansas no  
matter what happens,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is seriously considering  
seeking the seat that Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., will 
vacate when he retires in 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
